Someone has come to fix the floor of my kitchen, so I will pretend to still have a job and work from home while revising Too Hot to Handle.
If I can finally open this cursed file. (Damn OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm in.
And that's where it starts to drill really hard. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of turning my air purifier to full blast makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like wood shavings, so it's justified even if it's an anti-mask. And besides, I really do need to protect myself, don't I??
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he's gone.
The positive point is that I've finished re-reading chapter 4!
Chapter 5 is long, but a big suspense. Good work.
Currently doing search-replace operations on … ➡️  ellipsis character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But good, I'm committed. The most natural speeches are mostly fragmented, especially when people let themselves go with their emotions.
The craftsman is in the process of vacuuming, with a bit of luck, he'll soon be finished.
He went out (according to what I hear) to cut something. So I took a look to see where he is. It's far from being finished :(
More than 7 pages on chapter five. It still is my preferred chapter, and it's fairly well done. A few layout changes, and minor changes to switch to the active voice and improve concision. To be honest, I'd take a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still fiddling around in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope it's a good sign.
The craftsman has left!
He told me he had made a quote for the entire floor, but the owners were stingy and only paid for the small damaged area near the door. It's clearly better.
The house is airing out, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
